node.title: Katherine lockdown extended as NT records two new local COVID cases
node.description: The Northern Territory has recorded two new local cases of COVID-19 overnight, Chief Minister Michael Gunner says.

node.title: Police reduce capabilitiy to investigate work-related fatal road crashes
node.description: Documents reveal police have reduced their capability to investigate fatal road crashes for work-related health and safety breaches.

node.title: Protesters at Shelly Bay in Wellington say they will remain at site
node.description: The group occupying Shelly Bay in Wellington say they will remain at the site following last week's police presence.

node.title: Police do not suspect foul play in disappearance of Cindy Li
node.description: Police in Auckland say they do not believe there was any foul play in relation to the disappearance of Sandringham woman Cindy Li who was missing for 12 days before being located near her home.

node.title: Kyle Rittenhouse Tells Tucker Carlson He Backs BLM, Shooting Had 'Nothing To Do With Race'
node.description: "I'm not a racist person. I support the BLM movement. I support peacefully demonstrating," Rittenhouse said during his first TV appearance since his acquittal.

node.title: Paine back on the field, and appealing for Test selection as sexting scandal rolls on
node.description: Former Australian Test captain Tim Paine is back behind the stumps in his first game in months, as the sexting scandal which cost him the role continues to play out.

node.title: Gold Coast infectious diseases expert revealed as Queensland's new chief health officer
node.description: Gold Coast infectious diseases expert John Gerrard is named as Queensland's next chief health officer, becoming the permanent replacement for Jeannette Young.

node.title: El Salvador's President reveals plan for volcano-powered 'Bitcoin City'
node.description: In a rock concert-like atmosphere, Nayib Bukele uses a gathering of bitcoin enthusiasts to launch his latest idea: a seaside "Bitcoin City" at the base of a volcano.

node.title: 'That's a loophole': Queensland health authorities to examine gap in testing rules for interstate hotspot visits
node.description: Acting Chief Health Officer Peter Aitken says there is a "loophole" in the state's roadmap that would allow Queenslanders to visit hotspot locations interstate and return without being tested for COVID while they are there.
